nia -- tTwelve. Working Skillfully with Spilled Milk: Mindfulness in Clinical Psychology / rDimidjian, Sona -- tThirteen. A Living Tradition: Applications of Compassion Training / rDoty, James / Negi, Geshe Lobsang Tenzin -- tFourteen. The Heart of Education: Learning through Contemplative Experience / rStern, Aaron / Zajonc, Arthur -- tFifteen. Transformative Measures: Education and Secular Ethics / rSamten, Geshe Ngawang -- tAppendix: Questions and Answers with Five Thousand Monastics -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tSupporting Organizations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn illuminating record of dialogues between the Dalai Lama and some of today's most prominent scientists, philosophers, and contemplatives In 2013, during a historic six-day meeting at a Tibetan monastery in southern India, the Dalai Lama gathered with leading scientists, philosophers, and monks for in-depth discussions on the nature of reality, consciousness, and the human mind. This eye-opening book presents a record of those spirited and wide-ranging dialogues, featuring contributions from prominent scholars like Richard Davidson, Matthieu Ricard, Tania Singer, and Arthur Zajonc as they address such questions as: Does nature have a nature? Do you need a brain to be conscious? Can we change our minds and brains through meditation? Throughout, the contributors explore the exciting and sometimes surprising commonalities between Western scientific and Tibetan Buddhist methods of perceiving, investigating, and knowing. Part history, part state-of-the-field, part inspiration for the future, this book rigorously and accessibly explores what these two investigative traditions can teach each other, and what that can tell us about ourselves and the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site